               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc>
                     <supportDesc>
                        <support>
                           <p>Three texts, all inscribed on a single <material>white marble</material>
                              <objectType>block</objectType>; the block (<height unit="metre">0.81</height> x <width unit="metre">0.77</width>) has an area of rough tooling along the lower edge, which breaks into iii.16, suggesting that there was a moulding below, which was broken away to fit the stone for use in the wall (as is found on other re-used blocks in the wall). The stone must come from a composite monument of some kind, perhaps the wall of a building.</p>
                        </support>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout>The texts of i and ii must have started on the blocks above, and most of i, with much of iii was inscribed on a block to the left. i and ii both contain twenty-six lines, but these are not completely aligned with one another; l.26 of i ends on the same line as the first line of iii, while l.26 of ii ends above it; this probably indicates that the three documents were not inscribed simultaneously (although the lettering shows no marked variations).</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote>Letters standard second-/third-century forms, <height unit="metre">0.01</height>; dot for stops (not marked by Waddington or MAMA). Ligatures: <foreign xml:lang="grc">ΝΗ</foreign>, iii.6, <foreign xml:lang="grc">ΝΗΜ</foreign> iii.9, <foreign xml:lang="grc">ΜΝ</foreign>, <foreign xml:lang="grc">ΜΜ</foreign>, iii.15. We have not climbed up to the stone; measurements are therefore those of the MAMA team</handNote>
